Thank you for your cooperation.

post_text: The annual Sheridan School election is Tuesday, May 5, 2020, and will be held by mail ballot. There are two trustee seats up for election: One (1) Sheridan trustee for a three-year term and one (1) Alder trustee for a three-year term. The deadline to file as a candidate to be on the ballot has passed, but if you would like to be a write-in candidate, you can file until April 2. Please see the Elections tab on the school website for more information.
text: The annual Sheridan School election is Tuesday, May 5, 2020, and will be held by mail ballot. There are two trustee seats up for election: One (1) Sheridan trustee for a three-year term and one (1) Alder trustee for a three-year term. The deadline to file as a candidate to be on the ballot has passed, but if you would like to be a write-in candidate, you can file until April 2. Please see the Elections tab on the school website for more information.

post_text:
Hunters’ Safety Classes -
The first Sheridan Hunters' Safety class will be held on August 20, from 7:00 - 9:00 PM, in the Sheridan Elementary lunch room. A parent or guardian must accompany the student on this night. The other classes will be held August 22, 26, 29 September 4, 11 also from 7:00 - 9:00. A Field Day will be on September 15th at the Ruby Valley Gun Club at 1:00. A parent or guardian must also accompany the student on that day. To be eligible for this class you must be 11 years old by August 20. The students must attend all 12 hours of the class and also the Field Day to be certified. Some arrangements can be made for emergencies. If you have any questions, please call Jim Lane at 842-5984. You may sign up the first night in Sheridan.

post_text: The Sheridan Archery Team recently attended a regional archery tournament at Big Sky Archery, in Belgrade, MT. All five participants did a fantastic job, and showed great sportsmanship. Sofy took first place in the high school age group winning a gold medal, and she also won a trophy for being the top shooter of all the girls at the tournament. Jesica won a silver medal for second place in the high school division. Daniel won a silver medal for second place in the 6th, 7th, and 8th grade boys division. Kialar and Austin did a wonderful job shooting as well. Great job Sheridan Archers!!
text: The Sheridan Archery Team recently attended a regional archery tournament at Big Sky Archery, in Belgrade, MT. All five participants did a fantastic job, and showed great sportsmanship. Sofy took first place in the high school age group winning a gold medal, and she also won a trophy for being the top shooter of all the girls at the tournament. Jesica won a silver medal for second place in the high school division. Daniel won a silver medal for second place in the 6th, 7th, and 8th grade boys division. Kialar and Austin did a wonderful job shooting as well. Great job Sheridan Archers!!

May 15, 2019 at 2:05 PM ·

American Legion
‘Americanism and Government Survey’ Program

Sheridan – In April, Sheridan’s American Legion Post 89 completed the American Legion Americanism and Government Survey Program at Sheridan High School.
After all the surveys were scored, the Post selected winners in the 8th Grade and High School Senior levels. The first place winners in each category had their surveys forwarded for consideration at the State Level.
• At the 8th Grade Level, Katie Gronning took first place, Claira Haag second place and Jake Dvorak third place. All received a Certificate of Participation and the first place winner received a cash prize.
• At the High School Senior Level, Tyler Haag took first place, Zach Piper second place and Isaac Bendon third place. All received a Certificate of Participation and the first place winner received a cash prize.”

post_text:
Every year the third grade art class in Sheridan studies waterfowl and wetlands before drawing a realistic portrait of one particular duck or goose species. Students sometimes choose to enter their artwork in the Montana Junior Duck Stamp Contest. They may compete against up to 100 other students in their age category!
This year Sheridan sent six entries! Every student received a Certificate of Appreciation for entering their artwork. In the photo are, left to right, Hazalin Maddison, Eirik Reedy, Hannah Braaten, Riley Chisholm, Addison Stout, and Carli Wood. In addition, Hannah received special recognition for her art work, and Eirik and Hazalin received 2nd place ribbons!
A Celebration will take place in Stevensville in May, to which our students who participated are invited. This is a wonderful STEM program which bridges the disciplines by including Art - and so it's a STEAM masterpiece!

ATTENTION PARENTS!
Upcoming presentation for parents and community members regarding internet safety.

“Protecting Our Children: Keeping Up in a Modern World”

Wednesday, April 17, 6-7:30 pm in the CB Murray Library on the Sheridan High School Campus.

The presenter, Andrew Yedinak, is an Agent with the Montana Dept. of Justice, assigned to the ICAC (Internet Crimes Against Children) Task Force. He is a 16 year Law Enforcement Veteran and has worked for the Montana Dept. of Justice for just over 2 yrs. Prior to coming to Montana, he worked in the State of Illinois with the vast majority of his work being in Undercover Narcotics, which is what he initially did here in Montana. He has been with the ICAC Task Force for almost a year.

post_text: The freshman class of Sheridan High School returned from a 4 day Field Experience in Yellowstone Park. Hosted by Yellowstone Forever, the nonprofit partner of the national park,the field experience focused on three areas of scientific study: trophic cascades – when a change in one element ripples through an ecosystem; the geology of the northern range; and hot spots. Mr. Regnerus (Science) and Ms. Schendel (Art) accompanied the students on this STEAM project.

post_text: The first Sheridan Hunters' Safety class will be held on August 22, from 7:00 - 9:00 PM, in the Sheridan Elementary lunch room. A parent or guardian must accompany the student on this night. The other classes will be held August 27, September 5,12, 24,and 26, also from 7:00 - 9:00 PM. A Field Day will be on September 30th at the Ruby Valley Gun Club at 1:00. A parent or guardian must also accompany the student on that day. To be eligible for this class you must be 11 years old by August 22. The students must attend all 12 hours of the class and also the Field Day to be certified. Some arrangements can be made for emergencies. If you have any questions, please call Jim Lane at 842-5984. You may sign up the first night in Sheridan.

The Madison Ranger District is hosting it's 17th annual "Bear Creek Days" where over the next three days school children from West Yellowstone to Whitehall, Sheridan, Ennis, Twin Bridges, Alder and Harrison meet at the Bear Creek Campground to learn outdoor education activities led by many people from various federal, state and local agencies as well as public groups. Today 3rd and 4th graders panned for gold, learned about wildlife, plants, "Leave No Trace" and many other outdoor education activities.

post_text: Students in Sheridan's Small Business Management class competed in the One Montana Teenpreneur Challenge. Students came up with their own unique business idea, wrote a business summary, and pitched their idea via video. Overall, 15 business ideas were presented by 23 students from across Montana. Students were presented awards by Governor Bullock during a luncheon held at the Montan State Capitol. Isaac Bendon and Jasmine Driscoll tied for 2nd place while Zane Bowey placed 3rd. Riain Deavel and Sandy Moore both received honorable mention.

They are $14 each and the types that we have are: Four Cheese and Herb, Caramel Roll, Apple, Blueberry and Cream Cheese, Cherry, Cinnamon, Raspberry, and Strawberry and Cream Cheese. You may place an order by letting me know or any FCCLA member can also take your order. Orders will be taken until December 11 and will be delivered on December 19.
